ed in a native context. In the JVM, it seems to work well with a fresh class loader. I'm pondering a potential issue with the `DigestSchemeClassLoader` and how it loads classes, focusing on child-first loading for the `DigestScheme`. I wonder if having a child class extend a parent-loaded superclass creates a `LinkageError` due to duplicate references. It looks like it should be fine, though I’m keeping an eye on the classes’ protection domains.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering runtime initialization**\\n\\nI’m thinking about whether I need to build arguments for the runtime initialization of `DigestScheme`. If the class gets initialized at runtime in a native context, I wonder if the static initializer includes a `Class.forName` call. There might be a need for metadata, but if the class is in the image, then `Class.forName` should work. I also have to consider if adding runtime initialization could expose the `LogFactory` dynamically. That’s a bit tricky!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating git modifications**\\n\\nI’m working with the current build.gradle, which we’ve already modified by adding a Digest line. I shouldn’t revert those changes since they’re necessary. But if treated as a patch from HEAD, it could show the entire block, which might cause confusion. We need to isolate our changes. Inspecting the git diff for build.gradle against previous versions could help clarify things. However, I have to ensure we're correctly capturing only the necessary changes.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering uncommitted changes**\\n\\nI realize we can’t remove anything because of user changes. I need to note the existing uncommitted changes in my final answer. To avoid modifying build.gradle further, I should think about not adding to the broader diff. My addition of one line to an uncommitted block is relevant. Still, if the pipeline computes a diff from HEAD, it may include the whole block, which could be fine due to dynamic tests. But I'm contemplating removing the DigestScheme build argument to minimize impact on build.gradle.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating test strategies**\\n\\nI’m considering avoiding Class.forName in tests to cut down on dynamic access while using the new DigestScheme with a build arg. I wonder about call site coverage since class initialization should happen before the agent starts.\\n\\nFor JVM tests, instantiating DigestScheme initializes everything simply without dynamic loading patterns. However, if another test initializes it first, that could affect coverage. I should check AuthPolicy defaults to see if they rely on DigestScheme. It seems we might be okay with our constructor covering class$ without requiring a fresh classloader. But I’m wary of the unspecified test order in JUnit.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Assessing class loading and tests**\\n\\nI’m analyzing task-related call site `DigestScheme.class$` from the static initializer, which will be triggered naturally by a public API test. The idea of using a fresh classloader feels unnecessary if it focuses on dynamic helpers, especially given the existing patterns. But the rules advise against dynamic class loading for standard reflection. Perhaps it’s best to skip the fresh classloader test altogether if the class initializes at the test class load. The import itself doesn’t trigger it, but constructing `new DigestScheme` during the test body should be monitored for coverage, particularly with a runtime init build arg involved.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_iRlzcbmcoxqUVKQctam0GkmV|fc_02406d24921b1593016a048a3d82fc8192b1dce35c029eb1a7", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/commons-httpclient/commons-httpclient/3.0/src/test/java/commons_httpclient/commons_httpclient/DigestSchemeTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import java.net.URL;\nimport java.net.URLClassLoader;\n\n", "newText": ""}, {"oldText": "import org.graalvm.internal.tck.NativeImageSupport;\n", "newText": ""}, {"oldText": "public class DigestSchemeTest {\n    private static final String DIGEST_SCHEME_CLASS_NAME =\n            \"org.apache.commons.httpclient.auth.DigestScheme\";\n\n    @Test\n    void freshClassLoaderInitializationRunsLegacyClassHelper() throws Exception {\n        try (DigestSchemeClassLoader classLoader = newDigestSchemeClassLoader()) {\n            Class<?> digestSchemeClass = Class.forName(DIGEST_SCHEME_CLASS_NAME, true, classLoader);\n\n            assertThat(digestSchemeClass.getName()).isEqualTo(DIGEST_SCHEME_CLASS_NAME);\n        } catch (Error error) {\n            if (!NativeImageSupport.isUnsupportedFeatureError(error)) {\n                throw error;\n            }\n        }\n    }\n\n", "newText": "public class DigestSchemeTest {\n"}, {"oldText": "\n    private static DigestSchemeClassLoader newDigestSchemeClassLoader() {\n        URL location = DigestScheme.class.getProtectionDomain().getCodeSource().getLocation();\n        return new DigestSchemeClassLoader(new URL[] {location},\n                DigestSchemeTest.class.getClassLoader());\n    }\n\n    private static final class DigestSchemeClassLoader extends URLClassLoader {\n        private DigestSchemeClassLoader(URL[] urls, ClassLoader parent) {\n            super(urls, parent);\n        }\n\n        @Override\n        protected Class<?> loadClass(String name, boolean resolve) throws ClassNotFoundException {\n            synchronized (getClassLoadingLock(name)) {\n                if (DIGEST_SCHEME_CLASS_NAME.equals(name)) {\n                    Class<?> loadedClass = findLoadedClass(name);\n                    if (loadedClass == null) {\n                        loadedClass = findClass(name);\n                    }\n                    if (resolve) {\n                        resolveClass(loadedClass);\n                    }\n                    return loadedClass;\n                }\n                return super.loadClass(name, resolve);\n          